he varied local economic and political systems, and diverse social formations that predated European contact. These preexisting systems articulated with the expanding European economy and, in doing so, shaped its emergence. Moving beyond the confines of national or Atlantic histories to examine regional systems and their historical trajectories on a global scale, the studies within this volume draw examples from the Caribbean, Mesoamerica, North America, South America, Africa, and South Asia. While the contributions are rooted in substantive studies from different world areas, their overarching aim is to negotiate between global and local frames, revealing how the expanding world-system entangled the non-Western world in global economies, yet did so in ways that were locally articulated, varied and, often, non-European in their expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEconomic history. 0aSocial changexHistory. 0aSocial evolution. 0aSocial history. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Archaeology. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Douglas V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChouin, Gérard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcoran-Tadd, Noa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCorse, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCorse, Christopher R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHauser, Mark W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHofman, Corinne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Matt